c)

Duration was discarded because in the data dictionary specifically say that to include this variable for benchmark only. Also, this variable does not really seems to have relationship regards to the clients features. In addition, at the end of the call, the result is known straight away. So it seems to be sensible to discard this variable.

poutcome and pdays was stated on the data dictionary that it has missing values so it was also being discarded.

# discard  variables
bank_edited <- bank[c(-11, -13, -15)]

# convert y from yes/no to 0/1
bank_edited$response <- ifelse(bank_edited$y == "yes", 1, 0)
bank_edited$response <- as.numeric(bank_edited$response)
bank_edited <- bank_edited[-which(names(bank_edited) == 'y')]
colnames(bank_edited)[18] = "y"


# subsetting data into 2 categories
response_no <- subset(bank_edited, bank_edited[,18] == 0)
response_yes <- subset(bank_edited, bank_edited[,18] == 1)

# create training/testing set
sample <- sample(nrow(response_no), nrow(response_no) * 0.1)
no_testing <- response_no[sample,]
no_training<- response_no[-sample,]

sample2 <- sample(nrow(response_yes), nrow(response_yes) * 0.1)
yes_testing <- response_yes[sample2,]
yes_training<- response_yes[-sample2,]

test.df <- rbind(no_testing, yes_testing)
train.df <- rbind(no_training, yes_training)

## c)

plot p1 - job vs y: The proportion of clients across different job categories who subscribed to term deposit varies across the groups. This suggests that job could influence the decision to subscribe to term deposit.

p2 - education vs y: The proportion of clients across different education level who subscribe to term deposit slightly varies across the groups. This suggests that education may not have that strong influence on the decision.

p3 - marital vs y: The proportion of clients across marriage status group. The chart shows that there are a slight difference proportion of clients who subscribe to the term deposit. The divorced and married group have almost the same proportion where the single and unknown are just slightly higher. This suggests that the marital might have small influence on the decision.

p4 - default vs y: the proportion of the clients who has no credit on default have higher proportion on subscribe to the term deposit than the unknown group.

p5/p6 - house loan vs y: and loan vs y: This chart shows that the proportion of the clients who subscribe to the term deposit is no difference across the groups. This suggests that house loan and loan variables may not have influence on the decision to subscribe to term deposit.

p7 - day of the week vs y: The proportion of the days that the bank calls the clients have a slight variations across the days. However, the differences are very small. This sugguests that the day of the week variables may have small influence on the decision.

p8 - month vs y: There are large variations on the proportions across the months. This suggests that month could influence the decision on subscribe to term deposit.

p10 - contact vs y: here are large variations on the proportions across the months method of contact. This suggests that contact could influence the decision on subscribe to term deposit.

p11/p12/p15: relationship between age, campaign and previous to y respectively. From the boxplots, the median is similar across the group that subscribe and not subscribe to the term deposit. Hence it suggests that these variable, age, campaign and previous may not have influence on the decision to subscribe to term deposit.

p16/p18/p19/p20/21 - The relationship between emp_var_rate, consc_price_idx, cons_conf_idx, euribo3m and nr_employed to y. The box plots showed that there are siginificance in median across the subscribed and not subscribe group. This suggests that these variables contribute to the decision of the clients.

d)

euribor3m, emp_var_rate and month may be the most important variables in predicting the term deposit subscription. The euribor3m and emp_var_rate has a large different across the subscribe and not subscribe group. These 2 variables relate to the interest rate and the employment situation. From the charts, given the large difference, this 2 variables could contribute significantly to the prediction.

Lastly, month variable. From the chart, there are large variations across different month that the clients were being contacted. Some months have proportion of people agree to subscribed to the term deposit than other months. Hence, month could be an important predictor variable.

From the mis-classification rate, it seems that most of the models have a relatively low mis-classification rate at around 0.1. This indicate that the models perform relatively similar to each other. I would not choose random forest or xgboost as it is a blackbox modeling, we do not know which features they use and harder to explain. This left with logistic regression and Ridge. In this case, logistic regression could be a better choice as logistic regression is used to model a binary response variable. In addition, logistic regression handle the multilevels categorical variables by creating the dummy variable, in contrast to Ridge where it converted all categorical variables into 0/1 coding in a matrix form. Logistic regression is also easier to interpret as we can interpret the coefficients where we can see the significance of each variables to the response.

c)

In this analysis, we are interested to predicting if the client will subscribe a term deposit based on different client attributes and social and economic attributes.

In this analysis, we fitted the attributes into 4 different modelling approaches including logistic regression, ridge regression, random forest and XGBoost. Each models are evaluated based on how well they can predicted by calculating the mis-classification rates. The results showed that all of the models performed relatively well as they all have approximately 0.1 mis-classification rates. However, given the attributes of the clients, there are many categorical data, the best modeling approach would be to use the logistic regression as it can handle binary response(yes or no response) relatively well as well as can handle categorical data. Hence, it is recommend to use the logistic regression as the predicting approach in the future.

From this analysis, it is recommend to adjust the marketing approached as the following:

  1. We could target a certain jobs such as student and retired clients as we could see that the clients from these two categories have more proportion in subscribing to the term deposit.
  2. We could promote the marketing campaing during a certain month. From the analysis, there are more clients subscribed to the term deposit during March, September, October and December.
  3. When the Euribor 3 months rate is low and employment variation rate is low, it seems to be the most suitable period to contact customers as there are more likely to subscribe to the term deposit.
